			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Well I have finally done it...<a name="73264"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Feb 15 05 2:56 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>So far, I've found that WoW has fixed 95% percent of the annoyances of EQ.  I played many classes in EQ and my bard to level 70, with my guild to PoTime.
<br />

<br />
These are my WoW experiences so far, levelling a mage to 26 and a druid to level 30:
<br />

<br />
1) Zoning.. for the most part, there is NO zoning in WoW
<br />
2) Missed notes, fizzles - there are none.
<br />
3) Failed tradeskill combines are rare, and when it does fail, you don't lose the components.
<br />
4) WoW has nearly guaranteed skill ups on tradeskill items that are above your level, and if you can mem the recipe, you can make the item.
<br />
5) No weight limitations or encumbrance.
<br />
6) Automatic coinage adjustment.    You never have more than 100 of any coin type.
<br />
7) Not having to have your trader online to sell things.
<br />
8) Death is *almost* fun in WoW, and encourages you to try different tactics.
<br />
9) Players easily have the capability of killing lower level mobs (EQ dark blue mobs).  And with a little forethought and strategy, players can take on mobs 2 or 3 levels up, or multiple dark blues.  (not elite mobs, though.. they'll kick your butt)
<br />
10) You can have fun from the first minute you log into WoW, rather than having to wait to gather a group or raid.  There's always a quest (similar to EQ tasks) to work on, and most can be solo'd if you want.
<br />
11) mana and health regen is very accelerated compared to EQ, especially during downtime.  And you can accelerate it further by drinking for mana, and eating for hit points.
<br />
12) The graphics are better in so many ways than EQ.  More vibrant, better spell effects, better lighting, reflection off surfaces... more immersive.
<br />
13) There are many items in the game that are just for fun, and have no purpose.  Like pet birds, mechanical squirrels, etc.
<br />
14)The bugs seem far fewer than EQ too.
<br />
15)Add-on UI's can add a <i>ton</i> more functionality than is allowed in EQ.
<br />
16)They added a mechanism so that if you don't play for a while, you'll get accelerated xp when you come back for a time proportional to how long you were gone.  This helps you catch up with your friends.
<br />

<br />
There are some downsides:
<br />
1) Unlike EQ, characters are &quot;spec'd&quot; via aa-like points earned when levelling.  Therefore, they can't be good at everything.  Some may consider this an advantage, actually.
<br />
2) Many of the dungeons are cookie cutter.  You'll see the same tunnel/dungeon models in different zones.
<br />
3) The anti-training code makes mobs behave unrealistically, when the train stops (mobs zoom back to their original pathing).
<br />
4) Levelling seems quite a lot faster than EQ, and so you can have a level 60 within a couple of months of solid playtime.
<br />

<br />
On the whole, I've been playing WoW since Mid November, and I just don't see going back to EQ, with its many drawbacks.  I cancelled my EQ account.
<br />

<br />
If I quit WoW, I think I will be done with MMORPGs.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
